grammaticalStructure.name: Plain Copula だ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The plain, informal form of the copula です, used to state that 'A is B'. It is commonly used in casual speech and writing.

grammaticalStructure.name: A は B だ (A wa B da)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Noun 1 + は + Noun 2/Question Word + だ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The basic sentence structure 'A is B'. Here it is used as a question, 'Where is this place?'. The だ at the end makes it informal.

grammaticalStructure.name: Na-adjective + だ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to predicate a sentence with a na-adjective in the plain/informal form. It means 'It is (adjective)'.

grammaticalStructure.name: ～なさい (~nasai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A command form that is softer than the imperative form. It is often used by superiors to inferiors, such as parents talking to children or teachers to students.

grammaticalStructure.name: お + Verb Stem (Honorific)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A form of respectful language (keigo) used to show respect. In 'おあがり', it is used with the verb '上がる' (to eat/partake) to politely offer food.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜な (Sentence Ender)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: An informal sentence-ending particle, primarily used by men, to express emotion, emphasis, or a self-directed thought. It can convey a sense of admiration, wonder, or conviction.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜に行く (ni iku)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that the purpose of going somewhere is to do the action described by the verb. Here, it's 'asobi ni iku' (to go to play).

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜時 (toki)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Means 'when' or 'at the time of'. It connects a clause or phrase to describe the timing of an action. '遊びに行く時' means 'when you go out to play'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜って言う (tte iu)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: An informal way to quote someone or something. 'いってきますって言え' means 'say "ittekimasu"'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Imperative Form
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A verb form used to give a direct, and often harsh, command. '言え' is the imperative of '言う' (to say).

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜だろう/だろ (darou/daro)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to express a supposition or to seek confirmation from the listener. It translates to 'probably', 'I think', or '..., right?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜が (Sentence Ender)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: When used at the end of a clause or sentence, 'ga' can express reservation, contradiction, or soften a statement. Here it implies a contrary thought: '...but we're going together.'

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜んだ (nda)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to provide an explanation, add emphasis, or state something with a sense of discovery. 'いいんだ' means 'It is that it's good...'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜よな (yo na)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A combination of sentence-ending particles. 'yo' provides emphasis and 'na' seeks agreement or expresses a personal thought. It's like saying '..., right?' or '..., isn't it?' to oneself.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜たら (tara)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A conditional form that means 'if' or 'when'. '会ったら' means 'if you meet' or 'when you meet'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜しろ (shiro)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The plain imperative (command) form of the verb 'suru' (to do). 'あいさつしろ' is a direct command: 'Greet them!'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜っけ (kke)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used when the speaker is trying to recall something. It's like asking '...what was it again?' or '...I think it was, right?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ぞ (zo)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used mainly by men to add strong emphasis, assertion, or a warning. It is more forceful than 'yo'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Imperative Form + よ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A strong command or order, with the 'yo' particle added for emphasis. 'みならえよ' means 'Learn from her!' or 'Follow her example!'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Verb + てくる (~te kuru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that an action started in the past and is continuing up to the present, or an action that is directed towards the speaker.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence Final Particle か
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Turns a declarative sentence into a question.

grammaticalStructure.name: だろう / だろ (darou / daro)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to express supposition or to seek confirmation from the listener. Roughly translates to 'right?', 'isn't it?', or 'I think...'. The 'ろ' form is more informal and masculine.

grammaticalStructure.name: Noun/na-Adjective + じゃない
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to negate a noun or a na-adjective. The plain form of 'is not'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜なの / 〜のだ (~na no / ~no da)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used at the end of a sentence to provide an explanation, reason, or emphasis. The 'なの' form is often considered softer and is frequently used by women and children.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜てる / 〜でる (~teru / ~deru)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb te-form (without て/で) + てる/でる
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A colloquial contraction of the 〜ている / 〜でいる form, which indicates a continuous action or a state of being.

grammaticalStructure.name: Verb Stem + 方 (kata)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A suffix that attaches to the stem of a verb to mean 'way of doing (verb)'. For example, 言う (iu) becomes 言い方 (iikata).

grammaticalStructure.name: ごちそうさまでした (gochisousama deshita)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A fixed expression used after finishing a meal to thank the host, the chef, and for the food itself. It literally means 'it was a feast'.

grammaticalStructure.name: V-te kimasu (～てきます)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that the speaker will go somewhere, do an action, and then return. The phrase いってきます (from 行く + 来る) is a set expression derived from this pattern.

grammaticalStructure.name: Destination Particle に
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle 'に' is used after a place name to indicate the destination or direction of movement.

grammaticalStructure.name: Past Tense (~ta form)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates an action that was completed in the past. Formed by conjugating the verb into its -ta form. Used here in こわれた (kowareta), the past tense of 壊れる (kowareru).

grammaticalStructure.name: ～なくなる (~naku naru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates a change of state where something that was once possible is no longer possible. Formed by taking the adverbial form of a negative verb (e.g., 開かない -> 開かなく) and adding なる. Here, あかなくなった means 'it won't open anymore' or 'it has become impossible to open'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Chan Suffix (〜ちゃん)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A diminutive suffix added to names to show affection or familiarity. It is most often used for children, close female friends, family members, or pets. Using it for a father, like 'とーちゃん' (to-chan), is common for young children and conveys a sense of closeness and cuteness.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence Final Particle よ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle よ is added to the end of a sentence to indicate that the speaker is providing new information to the listener, to make a command, or to add emphasis to their statement.

grammaticalStructure.name: Colloquial Adjective Form (すごい -> すげー)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A common colloquial/slang transformation where the final 'い' of an i-adjective like すごい (sugoi) is changed to 'えー' (often written as 'え' or with a long vowel mark 'ー') to sound more casual or emphatic. The addition of a small っ (sokuon) as in すっげー adds further emphasis.

grammaticalStructure.name: ～てしまう (chau/jau form)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb te-form + しまう / ちゃう / じゃう
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that an action has been completed, often with a sense of finality, regret, or that it was done unintentionally. ねちまった is a colloquial contraction of 寝てしまった.

grammaticalStructure.name: か (Question Particle)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A particle placed at the end of a sentence to turn it into a question. The drawn-out かー indicates a more informal, questioning tone.

grammaticalStructure.name: ～ている (Progressive Form, Contraction)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb te-form + いる (contracted to てる or てん)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates an ongoing action or a resultant state. In '入ってんだろ', it's part of a chain of contractions from 入っている.

grammaticalStructure.name: ～んだ / ～のだ (Explanatory Particle)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Plain form verb/adjective/noun + んだ/のだ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to provide an explanation or context. The 'ん' in '入ってんだろ' is a contraction of 'の'.

grammaticalStructure.name: ～だろう (Conjecture/Tag Question)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to express a guess. When used with a rising intonation as 'だろ？', it seeks confirmation, like '..., right?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Casual Question Marker の
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle の at the end of a sentence with rising intonation creates an informal question. It's commonly used in casual conversation, especially by women and children, but also by men.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sokuon (っ) for Emphasis
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The small tsu (っ), known as sokuon, is often inserted into words, particularly adjectives and adverbs, to add emphasis. It creates a short pause, making the following sound more forceful. For example, あつい (atsui) becomes あっつい (attsui) to mean 'really hot'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence Ending Particle なあ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle なあ is used at the end of a sentence to express a feeling or emotion, often in a self-directed way (like talking to oneself). It can convey admiration, wonder, or a simple observation with feeling. The elongated version なぁー strengthens the emotional tone.

grammaticalStructure.name: Question Particle か
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Attached to the end of a sentence to turn it into a question. The sentence here is just the word '無理' (impossible).

grammaticalStructure.name: Emphasis Particle ぞ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle, primarily used by men, to add strong emphasis or assertion to a statement.

grammaticalStructure.name: Potential Form (いける)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Expresses ability or possibility. いける is the potential form of 行く (iku), meaning 'can go' or, more colloquially, 'can do it' or 'it works'.

grammaticalStructure.name: V-te oku (~ておく)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Expresses an action performed in preparation for something else, or to leave a situation as it is. In this context, そっとしておく means 'to leave (them) alone as they are'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Volitional Form (~おう)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Expresses intention, suggestion, or volition. It is often translated as 'Let's...' or 'I will...'. Here, おこう (volitional form of おく) combined with そっとして gives the meaning 'I think I'll just leave them be.'

grammaticalStructure.name: Quotative Particle と
grammaticalStructure.pattern: 「Quote」+ と + Verb (e.g., 言う, 思う, 書く)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle と is used to quote words, sounds, or thoughts. Here, 「風香る」と書いて (kaze kaoru to kaite) means 'written with the characters from (the phrase) kaze kaoru'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Makes No Sense / Don't Get It
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A set phrase used to express that something is incomprehensible or makes no sense. The particle が is often omitted in casual speech. Here, it is shortened further to わけわかんねー.

grammaticalStructure.name: Colloquial Negative Verb Ending (~ねー)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A very casual, often emphatic, contraction of the negative verb ending ～ない. It's a further slang version of ～ない -> ～んない -> ～んねー. E.g., 分からない (wakaranai) -> 分かんない (wakannai) -> 分かんねー (wakannee).

grammaticalStructure.name: Continuous Action (Colloquial)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A colloquial contraction of the ～ている form, used to express an ongoing action or state. In the panel, している (shiteiru) becomes してる (shiteru).

grammaticalStructure.name: Question Particle (Informal)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle の at the end of a sentence creates an informal question, often with a nuance of seeking explanation or a softer tone than using か.

grammaticalStructure.name: Honorific Suffix (~ちゃん)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A diminutive suffix used to show endearment, typically for children, close female friends, or family members.

grammaticalStructure.name: Te-form for Casual Request
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The te-form of a verb can be used by itself to make a casual request or a light command, as seen in 'これおして' (Kore oshite - Push this). It's a less formal version of '～てください' (te kudasai).

grammaticalStructure.name: Seeking Explanation with なの (na no)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The combination 'なの?' is used at the end of a sentence to ask a question seeking confirmation or explanation in a casual, often feminine or childish, manner. Here, '何か用なの？' (Nani ka you na no?) means 'Do you have some business (with me)?' or 'What do you need?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Movement Towards the Speaker (てくる)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The verb 'くる' (to come) attached to the te-form of another verb indicates that the action is directed towards the speaker or their current location. 'でてきた' (detekita) is the past tense of 'でてくる' (detekuru), meaning someone 'came out' towards the speaker's perspective.

grammaticalStructure.name: じゃない (ja nai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The informal negative form of です (desu), meaning 'is not'. When used at the end of a sentence with rising intonation (じゃない?), it functions as a tag question, similar to 'isn't it?' or 'right?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: どうかしたの (dou ka shita no)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: どうか + する (past tense) + の
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A common colloquial phrase used to ask someone what is wrong or what happened. Literally, 'Did something happen?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Verb Te-form for Commands/Requests
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The te-form of a verb can be used to make a light command or a request, especially in casual speech. For example, あいさつして (aisatsu shite) means 'Greet them!' or 'Say hi!'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜さん (~san)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A common, polite honorific title, equivalent to Mr., Mrs., or Ms. It is used for both men and women.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜な (na) Sentence Ending Particle
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used in informal speech, often by male speakers but also by children. It can express admiration, wonder, a strong conviction, or be used when talking to oneself.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜も (~mo)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A particle that means 'also' or 'too'. It replaces the topic marker は (wa) and the object marker を (o) when used.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜だ (~da)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The informal or plain form of the copula です (desu). It is used to state that something 'is' something else in casual conversation.

grammaticalStructure.name: だよ (da yo)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A casual and emphatic way to state something. It combines the plain copula 'だ' with the sentence-ending particle 'よ' for emphasis, often used when providing new information to the listener.

grammaticalStructure.name: な (Sentence End Particle)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used in casual, informal speech. It can be used to seek agreement, state a personal opinion, or add a softening effect. In 'じゃーな', it makes the farewell very casual and friendly.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜のに (noni)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb (casual) / i-adj / na-adj + な / Noun + な + のに
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to express a contrast between two clauses, similar to 'although' or 'even though'. It often carries a nuance of surprise, frustration, or complaint.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ちゃだめ (cha dame)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: V-te form (without て) + ちゃだめ
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A colloquial way of saying 〜てはいけない (te wa ikenai), meaning 'must not do' or 'should not do'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜なの (na no)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending pattern used to provide an explanation or state something with a soft, sometimes feminine or childlike, emphasis.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ていない (te inai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The negative form of the present progressive tense (~ている). It indicates that an action is not currently happening or a state does not exist. わかってない is a colloquial contraction of わかっていない.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ような (you na)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb (casual) / i-adj / na-adj + な / Noun + の + ような
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that something appears to be a certain way or seems like something else. It expresses similarity or appearance.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜じゃない (ja nai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The informal negative copula, used to state that something 'is not' something else. It's the plain form of ではありません (dewa arimasen).

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜の? (no?)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to form a question in an informal context. It often implies a desire for an explanation or shows a greater degree of personal interest than the standard question marker か.

grammaticalStructure.name: Receiving favors (~te morau)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Expresses that the speaker (or someone in the speaker's in-group) receives a favor from someone else. '買ってもらった' means '(I) had (someone) buy (it for me).'

grammaticalStructure.name: Nominalizer 'no'
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle 'の' can function as a pronoun, replacing a previously mentioned noun. '新しいの' means 'the new one'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Making suggestions (~you ka / ~ou ka)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to make a suggestion or invite someone to do something. '行こうか' means 'Shall we go?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Giving advice (~ta hou ga ii)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to give advice or a suggestion, meaning 'it would be better to...'. '交換した方がいい' means 'It's better to exchange it.'

grammaticalStructure.name: Continuous state (~te iru / ~teru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates an ongoing action or a state that resulted from a past action. The colloquial form is '〜てる'. '売ってる' means '(is) selling'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Recalling information (~kke)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used when the speaker is trying to recall something they are not sure about. 'あったっけ' means 'Was there...?' or 'I wonder if there was...'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Imperative (Archaic)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: An archaic and authoritative command form. It is stronger and more condescending than ～なさい. Used in fiction by characters of high status or, in this case, by a child for comedic effect. Example: おあがりたまえ (oagari tamae).

grammaticalStructure.name: Conjunction
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A polite way to connect two contrasting clauses. It softens the statement that follows. 'It is..., but...'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Prohibition (Informal)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A strong, informal prohibition meaning 'Don't...'. Often used by males or in casual situations. Example: えんりょするな (enryo suru na) - Don't hesitate!

grammaticalStructure.name: Colloquial contraction 〜ん
grammaticalStructure.explanation: In casual speech, a final の or もの can be contracted to ん. In 'こんなん', it's a contraction of 'こんなもの' (konna mono), meaning 'a thing like this'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Imperative form なさい (nasai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A command form that is softer than the plain imperative. It's often used by parents or teachers when speaking to children. 'してなさい' comes from the verb 'する'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Hearsay particle だって (datte)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that the preceding statement is hearsay. It can be translated as 'it is said that', 'I heard that', or 'they say'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Doing a favor for someone (〜てあげる)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: This pattern is used to express that the speaker (or someone in the speaker's in-group) does a favor for someone else. '留守番してあげよう' means 'I'll do you the favor of house-sitting with you'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Volitional Form (Let's / Shall I...)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb volitional form (e.g., 行こう, 食べよう, しよう)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The volitional form is used to express intention or make suggestions. When used by a speaker alone, as in 'あげよう', it indicates a decision or an offer: 'I'll do it'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜て (Casual Topic Marker)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A casual particle used to mark the topic of a sentence, often replacing は or というのは in informal speech.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜の (Informal Question)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence-ending particle used to ask a question in an informal, softer way. Commonly used by women and children.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜かぁ (Particle of Realization)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A sentence final particle used when one comes to a realization or is contemplating something. The long vowel adds emphasis.

grammaticalStructure.name: Verb (dictionary form) + 方 (ほう)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to mean 'the side for doing X' or 'the way of doing X'. In this case, 'the side you hold (the bowl) with'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ている / 〜てる (Contraction)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The 〜ている form expresses a continuing action or a state of being. In casual speech, 〜ている is often contracted to 〜てる. 知っている (to be in the state of knowing) becomes しってる.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜だな (da na)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A combination of the copula だ and the sentence-ending particle な. It's used to express a thought or feeling with some conviction, often when talking to oneself or making an observation.

grammaticalStructure.name: ちゃう / じゃう (chau / jau)
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb (て-form) + ちゃう / Verb (で-form) + じゃう
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A colloquial contraction of 〜てしまう / 〜でしまう, used to express that an action has been completed, often with a nuance of regret, surprise, or that it happened unintentionally. ねちゃった is the past tense of ねちゃう, which is a contraction of 寝てしまう (nete shimau).

grammaticalStructure.name: V-ている (V-te iru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates a continuing action or a resulting state. In '壊れている', it indicates the state of being broken.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence Ending Particle よ (yo)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used at the end of a sentence to add emphasis, assert a strong opinion, or to inform the listener of something new.

grammaticalStructure.name: Verb Negative Form (nai-form)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to negate verbs. For Godan verbs like 開く (aku), the final 'u' vowel changes to 'a' before adding ない, resulting in 開かない (akanai).

grammaticalStructure.name: Topic Marker は (wa)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Marks the topic of the sentence. The particle is read as 'wa', not 'ha'.

grammaticalStructure.name: V-てくる (V-te kuru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that an action is directed towards the speaker, or that a change has been happening up to the present. '戻ってくる' means 'to come back'.

grammaticalStructure.name: V-ている contraction (V-teru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A common colloquial contraction of the V-ている (te iru) form. 'もどってきてる' is a contraction of 'もどってきている'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence Ending Particle かな (kana)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used at the end of a sentence to express doubt or wonder, similar to 'I wonder...'. The trailing 'ぁ' indicates elongation for emphasis.

grammaticalStructure.name: Trailing off / Hesitation (Ellipsis)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The ellipsis (three dots) is used to indicate a pause, hesitation, or speech that trails off. It conveys uncertainty or that the speaker is thinking about what to say next, as seen in 「え… あの…」.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜ています (~te imasu)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates a continuing action or a state resulting from a past action. The phrase 'おじゃましています' is a set expression used when entering someone's home, literally meaning 'I am disturbing you'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜てください (~te kudasai)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A polite way to make a request to someone. '聞いて下さい' means 'Please listen' or 'Please hear me out'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜から (~kara)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates the reason or cause for something. 'わかるから' means 'because I understand'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Passive Form (れる/られる)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used when the subject is the recipient of an action. '思われる' is the passive form of '思う' (to think), meaning 'to be thought of' or 'to be considered'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜でしょう (~deshou)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Expresses probability or seeks confirmation from the listener. '思われるでしょうが' means 'I imagine you think it's..., but...'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜んで (~n de)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A colloquial contraction of 〜ので, used to provide a reason. '壊れてるんで' means 'because it's broken'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜なくなる (~naku naru)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates a change to a state of 'not doing' or 'being unable to do' something. '動かなくなる' means 'to become unable to move'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜てしまう / 〜ちゃう (~te shimau / ~chau)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that an action has been completed, often with a sense of regret, surprise, or finality. 'なっちゃった' is the colloquial past tense form of 'なってしまった' (from なる), meaning 'ended up becoming'.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜んです (~n desu)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to provide an explanation, reason, or emphasis for a situation. Here, it explains why she is asking for help.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜てもらう (~te morau)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to express receiving a favor from someone, where the speaker is the beneficiary of the action. '引っぱってもらう' means 'to have someone pull (for me)'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Potential Form + ませんか
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Potential Verb stem + ませんか
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Combines the potential form (to be able to do) with the negative question form (~masen ka?) to make a very polite request. 'もらえませんか' is the potential form of 'もらう' (to receive), literally asking 'Am I not able to receive (the favor of)...?', which translates to 'Could you please...?' or 'Would you mind...?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: Honorific Suffix 〜ちゃん (-chan)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A diminutive suffix added to names or kinship terms, primarily for children, close friends, or young women. It conveys a sense of familiarity and affection. Here, it is used with 姉 (older sister) to create a casual and affectionate term.

grammaticalStructure.name: Particle よ for Emphasis
grammaticalStructure.explanation: The particle 'よ' is used at the end of a sentence to strongly state an opinion, give a warning, or provide information the listener may not know. The trailing ー (in よー) adds extra emphasis and a casual, drawn-out tone.

grammaticalStructure.name: Try to do (Suggestion/Soft Command)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A gentle command or suggestion, typically used by someone of higher status (like a parent or older sibling) towards someone of lower status (like a child). It means 'try doing...' or 'why don't you...'. The elongated ん (in ごらーん) makes the suggestion sound more casual and inviting.

grammaticalStructure.name: ている (てる - contracted form)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates an ongoing action or a state of being. The 〜ている form is often contracted to 〜てる in casual speech.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence + の?
grammaticalStructure.explanation: An informal way to ask a question, often used by women and children. It softens the question and can imply a desire for explanation or a friendly tone.

grammaticalStructure.name: 〜じゃないか / 〜じゃない?
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Noun/Adjective + じゃないか / じゃない?
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used at the end of a sentence to express confirmation, suggestion, or a rhetorical question, similar to 'isn't it?' or 'don't you think?'.

grammaticalStructure.name: けど
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A conjunction used to connect two clauses. It can indicate contrast ('but', 'although'), or be used to soften a statement or introduce a topic.

grammaticalStructure.name: Humble Form (Kenjougo)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A humble expression used to talk about one's own actions towards someone of higher status. Here, おかけする is the humble form of かける (to cause). おかけしまして is a formal connective form of this.

grammaticalStructure.name: Formal Apology
grammaticalStructure.pattern: 申し訳ありません (Moushiwake arimasen)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A very polite and formal way to say 'I'm sorry' or 'It is inexcusable.'

grammaticalStructure.name: Passive Form
grammaticalStructure.pattern: Verb (u-verb) stem + aれる, Verb (ru-verb) stem + られる, する -> される
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that an action is done to the subject. Here, バカにされる (from the verb phrase バカにする) means 'to be made a fool of (by someone).'

grammaticalStructure.name: Listing Reasons with ~し
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Used to list multiple reasons or states, implying there may be others. Here, it lists one reason for her embarrassment.

grammaticalStructure.name: Resulting in... (~ことになる)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: Indicates that something has been decided or has come to a certain state, often not by the speaker's own will. The phrase 'なんでこんな事に' is a shortened form of 'なんでこんなことになったんだ' (Why did it turn out like this?).

grammaticalStructure.name: How should I put it...
grammaticalStructure.pattern: なんて言うか (nante iu ka)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A common conversational phrase used when one is searching for the right words or trying to express something unclearly. ゆーか is a colloquial pronunciation of 言うか.

grammaticalStructure.name: Casual Negative Imperative (な)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A casual and strong command not to do something. For example, '気にするな' (ki ni suru na) means 'don't worry about it'. It is a more forceful and informal version of 〜ないでください.

grammaticalStructure.name: Sentence-Ending Particle Combination (よね)
grammaticalStructure.explanation: A combination of particles 'yo' (emphasis) and 'ne' (seeking agreement). It's used when the speaker is asserting something they are fairly sure about and wants the listener's confirmation. It translates to '..., right?!' or '..., isn't it?!'.
